Alaska ([/əˈlæskə/](/Help:IPA/English) &#32; [ⓘ](/File:En-us-Alaska.ogg) ə-LASS-kə) is a [non-contiguous](/Non-contiguous_United_States) [U.S. state](/U.S._state) perched on the ragged edge of [North America](/North_America). It’s part of the [Western United States](/Western_United_States) region, and if you’re counting states that aren't physically connected to the rest, it's one of two, the other being [Hawaii](/Hawaii). Alaska holds the distinction of being the northernmost, westernmost, and, thanks to the [Aleutian Islands](/Aleutian_Islands) dipping into the eastern hemisphere across the [180th meridian](/180th_meridian), the easternmost state. To its east lies the imposing Canadian territory of [Yukon](/Yukon) and the province of [British Columbia](/British_Columbia). Across the [Bering Strait](/Bering_Strait), Russia’s [Chukotka Autonomous Okrug](/Chukotka_Autonomous_Okrug) is a mere maritime whisper away. The frigid embrace of the [Arctic Ocean](/Arctic_Ocean), with its [Chukchi](/Chukchi_Sea) and [Beaufort](/Beaufort_Sea) Seas, defines its northern boundary, while the vast [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean) lies to its south. It’s a semi-exclave, a piece of the U.S. set apart, and frankly, the largest exclave on the planet.

Alaska is a behemoth in terms of area, a sprawling expanse that eclipses [Texas](/Texas), [California](/California), and [Montana](/Montana) combined. It’s the seventh-largest subnational division globally. Yet, despite its immense size, it’s a sparsely populated place, ranking third-least populous and most sparsely populated among U.S. states. With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it’s the most populous territory in North America north of the [60th parallel](/60th_parallel_north), outnumbering northern Canada and [Greenland](/Greenland) by a significant margin. &#91;6&#93; Its urban centers are massive, with [Anchorage](/Anchorage,_Alaska) being the largest city, home to nearly half of Alaska’s inhabitants. Even its capital, [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska), is one of the largest cities in the United States by area.

The Indigenous peoples, the [Alaska Natives](/Alaska_Natives), have called this land home for millennia. It’s widely accepted that this region was the gateway, the first step for humanity’s journey into North America via the [Bering land bridge](/Bering_land_bridge). The [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire) was the first European power to actively impose its presence, establishing [Russian America](/Russian_colonization_of_North_America) in the 18th century, a vast dominion that stretched across much of the current state and fostered a distinct [Alaskan Creole](/Alaskan_Creole_people) population. &#91;7&#93; The sheer cost and logistical nightmare of maintaining such a distant territory led to its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for a mere $7.2 million – a pittance, even in 2024 dollars ($162 million). After a period of administrative flux, it was finally organized as a [territory](/Territories_of_the_United_States) in May 1912, before grudgingly being admitted as the 49th state in January 1959. &#91;8&#93;

Alaska’s wealth of natural resources—[commercial fishing](/Commercial_fishing_in_Alaska), the relentless extraction of [natural gas](/Natural_gas_in_Alaska) and oil—have propelled it to one of the highest [per capita incomes](/List_of_U.S._states_by_GDP_per_capita) in the nation, despite its comparatively small economy. Military bases and the relentless influx of [tourism](/Tourism_in_Alaska) also fuel its coffers. More than half of Alaska is federally owned, a vast expanse of [national forests](/United_States_National_Forest), [national parks](/List_of_national_parks_of_the_United_States), and [wildlife refuges](/National_wildlife_refuge). It’s also a state that largely shuns organized religion, ranking among the [most irreligious states](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_religiosity), and it was among the first to embrace legal recreational marijuana. The Indigenous population remains significant, the second highest proportion of any U.S. state, after Hawaii, at over 15 percent. &#91;9&#93;

### Etymology

The name "Alaska" ( [Russian](/Russian_language): Аля́ска, transliterated: Aljáska ) first appeared during the [Russian colonial period](/Russian_America), specifically referring to the [Alaska Peninsula](/Alaska_Peninsula). Its origin lies in an [Aleut-language](/Aleut_language) term, *alaxsxaq*, meaning "the mainland" or, more poetically, "the object towards which the action of the sea is directed." &#91;10&#93; &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93;

