### History

*   Main articles: [Prehistory of Alaska](/Prehistory_of_Alaska) and [History of Alaska](/History_of_Alaska)

#### Pre-colonization

*   Main article: [Alaska Natives](/Alaska_Natives)

For millennia before Europeans cast their shadows across the land, Alaska was home to numerous Indigenous peoples. Evidence gleaned from linguistic studies and DNA analysis points to this region as the primary entry point for the initial settlement of North America, facilitated by the now-vanished [Bering land bridge](/Bering_land_bridge). &#91;13&#93; &#91;14&#93; At the [Upward Sun River site](/Upward_Sun_River_site) in the [Tanana Valley](/Tanana_Valley), the remains of a six-week-old infant were discovered. This child's DNA revealed a genetic lineage distinct from other Native groups already present in the [New World](/New_World) by the close of the [Pleistocene](/Pleistocene) epoch. Ben Potter, the archaeologist from the [University of Alaska Fairbanks](/University_of_Alaska_Fairbanks) who led the excavation in 2013, christened this ancestral population the [Ancient Beringian](/Ancient_Beringian). &#91;15&#93;

In what is now Southeast Alaska, extending into [British Columbia](/British_Columbia) and the [Yukon](/Yukon), the [Tlingit people](/Tlingit_people) forged a society structured by a [matrilineal](/Matrilineal) system of inheritance and descent. The [Haida](/Haida_people), renowned for their distinctive artistry, also inhabited the Southeast. The [Tsimshian](/Tsimshian) people migrated to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, granted permission by President [Grover Cleveland](/Grover_Cleveland) and later the U.S. Congress to establish a settlement on [Annette Island](/Annette_Island) and found the town of [Metlakatla, Alaska](/Metlakatla,_Alaska). All three of these groups, alongside other [Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Pacific_Northwest_Coast), endured devastating [smallpox](/Smallpox) outbreaks from the late 18th to the mid-19th centuries. The most catastrophic [epidemics](/Epidemics) struck in the 1830s and 1860s, leaving a trail of high fatalities and societal upheaval. &#91;16&#93;

#### Colonization

*   Main articles: [Russian colonization of North America](/Russian_colonization_of_North_America), [Alaskan Creole people](/Alaskan_Creole_people), [Department of Alaska](/Department_of_Alaska), [District of Alaska](/District_of_Alaska), [Fairbanks Gold Rush](/Fairbanks_Gold_Rush), [Kobuk River Stampede](/Kobuk_River_Stampede), [Nome Gold Rush](/Nome_Gold_Rush), and [Alaska Purchase](/Alaska_Purchase)

[Russian settlement of St. Paul's Harbor, present-day Kodiak town, Kodiak Island, 1814](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Kodiak_1814.jpg/640px-Kodiak_1814.jpg)
Miners and prospectors ascend the [Chilkoot Trail](/Chilkoot_Trail) during the 1898 [Klondike Gold Rush](/Klondike_Gold_Rush).

Some researchers propose that the first Russian settlement in Alaska dates back to the 17th century. &#91;17&#93; This theory posits that in 1648, several [koches](/Koch_(boat)) from [Semyon Dezhnyov](/Semyon_Dezhnyov)'s expedition were driven ashore in Alaska by a storm, leading to the establishment of this settlement. This claim rests on the testimony of the [Chukchi](/Chukchi_people) geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who visited Alaska between 1764 and 1765 and reported on a village on the Kheuveren River inhabited by "bearded men" who "pray to the [icons](/Icons)". Some contemporary scholars associate the Kheuveren River with the [Koyuk River](/Koyuk_River). &#91;18&#93;

The generally accepted first European vessel to reach Alaska was the *St. Gabriel*, commanded by surveyor [M. S. Gvozdev](/Mikhail_Gvozdev) and navigated by assistant navigator [I. Fyodorov](/Ivan_Fyodorov_(navigator)) on August 21, 1732. This occurred during an expedition led by Siberian Cossack A. F. Shestakov and Russian explorer [Dmitry Pavlutsky](/Dmitry_Pavlutsky) (1729–1735). &#91;19&#93; Another significant European encounter with Alaska took place in 1741, when [Vitus Bering](/Vitus_Bering) led an [expedition](/Second_Kamchatka_expedition) for the Russian Navy aboard the *St. Peter*. Upon the crew's return to Russia with [sea otter](/Sea_otter) pelts described as the finest fur in the world, small groups of [fur traders](/Fur_trade) began to sail from Siberia towards the Aleutian Islands. The first permanent European settlement was established in 1784.

Between 1774 and 1800, [Spain](/Viceroyalty_of_New_Spain) dispatched several [expeditions to Alaska](/Spanish_expeditions_to_the_Pacific_Northwest) to assert its territorial claims in the Pacific Northwest. In 1789, a Spanish settlement and [fort](/Fort_San_Miguel) were constructed in [Nootka Sound](/Nootka_Sound). These Spanish ventures left their mark on the region through place names such as [Valdez](/Valdez,_Alaska), [Bucareli Sound](/Bucareli_Sound), and [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska). Later, the [Russian-American Company](/Russian-American_Company) spearheaded a more extensive colonization effort throughout the early to mid-19th century. [Sitka](/Sitka,_Alaska), known as [New Archangel](/New_Archangel) from 1804 to 1867, situated on [Baranof Island](/Baranof_Island) within the [Alexander Archipelago](/Alexander_Archipelago) of what is now [Southeast Alaska](/Southeast_Alaska), became the capital of [Russian America](/Russian_colonization_of_North_America). It maintained this status even after the colony was transferred to the United States. The Russians, however, never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony proved to be perpetually unprofitable. Vestiges of Russian presence persist in place names and church architecture throughout southeastern Alaska. &#91;20&#93;

In 1867, [William H. Seward](/William_H._Seward), the [United States Secretary of State](/United_States_Secretary_of_State) under President [Andrew Johnson](/Andrew_Johnson), finalized the [Alaska Purchase](/Alaska_Purchase) with Russia, a transaction widely derided as "Seward's Folly." The sale, for $7.2 million, was orchestrated by Russian emperor [Alexander II](/Alexander_II_of_Russia). &#91;21&#93; &#91;22&#93; The official transfer occurred on March 30, 1867, with the formal ceremony taking place six months later in Sitka. The raising of the U.S. flag at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867, marked the symbolic transfer. This date is now commemorated as [Alaska Day](/Alaska_Day), a legal holiday.

Initially, Alaska was under loose military governance. In 1884, it was organized as a [district](/District_of_Alaska), with a governor appointed by the U.S. president. A federal [district court](/United_States_territorial_court) was established in Sitka. For the first decade of American administration, Sitka was the sole community inhabited by American settlers, who organized what they called "a provisional city government"—Alaska's first municipal government, though not legally recognized as such. &#91;23&#93; Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally [incorporate as cities](/Municipal_corporation) wouldn't arrive until 1900, and the concept of [home rule](/Home_rule) for cities remained severely restricted, if not entirely absent, until statehood was achieved in 1959.

#### U.S. territorial incorporation

*   Main articles: [Organic act § List of organic acts](/Organic_act), and [Territory of Alaska](/Territory_of_Alaska)

From the 1890s into the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the neighboring Yukon Territory drew thousands of prospectors and settlers. Between 1879 and 1920, Alaska yielded over $460,000,000 in mineral production—a sum equivalent to $7,220,166,113 in 2024. &#91;24&#93; In 1912, Alaska was officially incorporated as an organized territory. Its capital, previously in Sitka, was relocated north to [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska) in 1906. The construction of the [Alaska Governor's Mansion](/Alaska_Governor%27s_Mansion) commenced that same year. European immigrants, primarily from Norway and Sweden, also established communities in Southeast Alaska, contributing to the fishing and logging industries.

[U.S. troops navigate snow and ice during the Battle of Attu in May 1943.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/US_troops_in_Attu_1943.jpg/640px-US_troops_in_Attu_1943.jpg)

During [World War II](/World_War_II), the [Aleutian Islands Campaign](/Aleutian_Islands_Campaign) saw intense fighting focused on [Attu](/Attu_Island), [Agattu](/Agattu), and [Kiska](/Kiska_Island), all of which were occupied by the [Empire of Japan](/Empire_of_Japan). &#91;a&#93; The Japanese occupation resulted in the deaths of one American civilian and two [United States Navy](/United_States_Navy) personnel. Approximately 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan, with nearly half of the Aleuts succumbing during their captivity. &#91;25&#93; [Unalaska](/Unalaska)/[Dutch Harbor](/Dutch_Harbor) and [Adak](/Adak,_Alaska) emerged as crucial bases for the [United States Army](/United_States_Army), [United States Army Air Forces](/United_States_Army_Air_Forces), and the United States Navy. As part of the U.S. [Lend-Lease](/Lend-Lease) program, American warplanes were flown through [Canada](/Canada) to [Fairbanks](/Fairbanks,_Alaska) and then to [Nome](/Nome,_Alaska), where Soviet pilots took possession of them for combat against the German invasion of the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). The construction of military installations spurred population growth in several Alaskan cities.

#### Statehood

*   See also: [Alaska Statehood Act](/Alaska_Statehood_Act), [Admission to the Union](/Admission_to_the_Union), and [List of U.S. states by date of admission to the Union](/List_of_U.S._states_by_date_of_admission_to_the_Union)

[Bob Bartlett and Ernest Gruening, Alaska's inaugural U.S. Senators, hold the 49-star U.S. Flag after the admission of Alaska as the 49th state.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Gruening_Bartlett_49_star_flag.jpg/640px-Gruening_Bartlett_49_star_flag.jpg)

The quest for statehood was a persistent ambition for [James Wickersham](/James_Wickersham) early in his congressional tenure. &#91;26&#93; Decades later, the statehood movement gained significant traction following a territorial referendum in 1946. The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention were subsequently formed. Statehood proponents also navigated considerable political opposition, both within Congress and Alaska itself. Statehood was finally approved by the U.S. Congress on July 7, 1958, and Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959. &#91;27&#93;

##### Good Friday earthquake

*   Main article: [1964 Alaska earthquake](/1964_Alaska_earthquake)

On March 27, 1964, the catastrophic [Good Friday earthquake](/1964_Alaska_earthquake) struck, claiming 133 lives and obliterating several villages and sections of coastal communities, primarily due to the ensuing [tsunamis](/Tsunamis) and landslides. It registered as the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a [moment magnitude](/Moment_magnitude_scale) of 9.2—over a thousand times more potent than the [1989 San Francisco earthquake](/1989_Loma_Prieta_earthquake). &#91;28&#93; The timing of the quake (5:36 pm), its occurrence in spring, and the epicenter's location were all cited as factors that likely spared thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.

The Good Friday earthquake reverberated for 4 minutes and 38 seconds. An immense 600-mile (970 km) rupture along the fault line shifted land by up to 60 feet (18 m), releasing approximately 500 years of accumulated stress. The resulting [soil liquefaction](/Soil_liquefaction), fissures, landslides, and other ground failures inflicted severe structural damage on numerous communities and caused widespread property destruction. [Anchorage](/Anchorage,_Alaska) suffered extensive damage to its housing and infrastructure, especially in landslide-prone areas along [Knik Arm](/Knik_Arm). Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, sections near [Kodiak](/Kodiak_Island) were permanently elevated by 30 feet (9 m). Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of [Turnagain Arm](/Turnagain_Arm) near [Girdwood](/Girdwood,_Anchorage) and [Portage](/Portage_(Anchorage)) subsided by as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), necessitating reconstruction and fill to raise the [Seward Highway](/Seward_Highway) above the new high [tide](/Tide) line. &#91;29&#93;

In [Prince William Sound](/Prince_William_Sound), [Port Valdez](/Port_of_Valdez) experienced a massive underwater landslide that resulted in 32 fatalities, stemming from the collapse of the [Valdez](/Valdez,_Alaska) city harbor and docks, and impacting individuals aboard a docked ship. Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami obliterated the village of [Chenega](/Chenega,_Alaska), killing 23 of its 68 residents; survivors managed to escape to higher ground. Subsequent tsunamis severely impacted [Whittier](/Whittier,_Alaska), [Seward](/Seward,_Alaska), Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as causing damage in British Columbia, [Washington](/Washington_(state)), [Oregon](/Oregon), and California. &#91;30&#93; Tsunamis also reached Hawaii and Japan. Evidence of ground motion directly attributable to the earthquake was even reported from [Florida](/Florida) and [Texas](/Texas).

Alaska had never before faced such a widespread disaster in a densely populated area and possessed minimal resources to manage its aftermath. In Anchorage, at the behest of geologist [Lidia Selkregg](/Lidia_Selkregg), the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority assembled a team of 40 scientists—geologists, soil scientists, and engineers—to assess the earthquake's impact on the city. &#91;31&#93; This group, known as the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was led by [Ruth A. M. Schmidt](/Ruth_A._M._Schmidt), a geology professor at the [University of Alaska Anchorage](/University_of_Alaska_Anchorage). The scientific team clashed with local developers and business owners eager to rebuild immediately, as the scientists prioritized identifying future hazards to ensure the safety of rebuilt infrastructure. &#91;32&#93; Their comprehensive report was submitted on May 8, 1964, just over a month after the earthquake. &#91;31&#93; &#91;33&#93;

The U.S. military, with a significant presence in Alaska, mobilized immediately to provide assistance. The U.S. Army swiftly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to aid Anchorage residents, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez. &#91;34&#93; Following recommendations from military and civilian leaders, President [Lyndon B. Johnson](/Lyndon_B._Johnson) declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake. The U.S. Navy and [U.S. Coast Guard](/United_States_Coast_Guard) deployed vessels to remote coastal communities to address immediate needs. Adverse weather conditions hampered air rescue and observation efforts on the day following the quake, but conditions improved on Sunday the 29th, allowing for the deployment of rescue helicopters and observation aircraft. &#91;34&#93; A massive military airlift commenced, delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and essential supplies to Alaska. &#91;35&#93;

Broadcast journalist [Genie Chance](/Genie_Chance) played a crucial role in recovery and relief efforts, maintaining a steady presence on [KENI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KENI) radio in Anchorage for over 24 consecutive hours, broadcasting calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building. &#91;36&#93; The city's police chief effectively designated her as the public safety officer. &#91;36&#93; Chance provided real-time updates on the unfolding catastrophe, serving as the voice of the public safety office. She coordinated response efforts, matched available resources to community needs, disseminated information about shelters and food supplies, relayed messages between loved ones, and facilitated family reunions. &#91;37&#93;

In the longer term, the [U.S. Army Corps of Engineers](/U.S._Army_Corps_of_Engineers) spearheaded the reconstruction of roads, debris removal, and the establishment of new town sites for communities completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million. &#91;35&#93; The [West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center](/West_Coast_and_Alaska_Tsunami_Warning_Center) was established directly in response to the disaster. Federal disaster relief funds financed reconstruction and provided crucial financial support to Alaska's devastated government infrastructure, injecting hundreds of millions of dollars that helped maintain the state's financial stability until the discovery of vast oil reserves at [Prudhoe Bay](/Prudhoe_Bay). Under orders from the [U.S. Defense Department](/United_States_Department_of_Defense), the [Alaska National Guard](/Alaska_National_Guard) created the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to prepare for future disasters. &#91;34&#93;

##### Oil boom

The discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay in 1968 and the completion of the [Trans-Alaska Pipeline System](/Trans-Alaska_Pipeline_System) in 1977 triggered a significant oil boom. Royalty revenues from petroleum have sustained substantial state budgets since 1980.

[Oil pooled on rocks on the shore of Prince William Sound after the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Exxon_Valdez_oil_spill_on_shoreline.jpg/640px-Exxon_Valdez_oil_spill_on_shoreline.jpg)

Oil extraction wasn't the sole economic driver of Alaska's land. In the latter half of the 20th century, tourism emerged as a vital revenue stream. This industry gained momentum after World War II, as military personnel stationed in the region returned home, extolling its natural beauty. The [Alcan Highway](/Alaska_Highway), constructed during the war, and the [Alaska Marine Highway System](/Alaska_Marine_Highway), completed in 1963, significantly improved the state's accessibility. Tourism has become increasingly pivotal to Alaska's economy, attracting over 1.4 million visitors annually. &#91;38&#93;

With tourism's growing economic importance, environmental concerns gained prominence. The [Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act](/Alaska_National_Interest_Lands_Conservation_Act) (ANILCA) of 1980 designated an additional 53.7 million acres (217,000 km<sup>2</sup>) for the [National Wildlife Refuge system](/National_Wildlife_Refuge), incorporated portions of 25 rivers into the [National Wild and Scenic Rivers System](/National_Wild_and_Scenic_Rivers_System), added 3.3 million acres (13,000 km<sup>2</sup>) to [National Forest lands](/National_forest_(United_States)), and set aside 43.6 million acres (176,000 km<sup>2</sup>) as [National Park land](/National_Park_Service). Consequently, Alaska now encompasses two-thirds of all American national parklands. Today, the [Federal Government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States) owns more than half of Alaska's land. &#91;39&#93;

In 1989, the [Exxon Valdez](/Exxon_Valdez) struck a reef in Prince William Sound, releasing over 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil that fouled 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline. The ongoing debate between development and conservation is evident in the contentious discussions surrounding oil drilling in the [Arctic National Wildlife Refuge](/Arctic_National_Wildlife_Refuge) and the proposed [Pebble Mine](/Pebble_Mine). &#91;40&#93;

### Geography

*   Main article: [Geography of Alaska](/Geography_of_Alaska)

Situated at the northwesternmost point of North America, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States. Its easternmost longitude is also a peculiarity, due to the [Aleutian Islands](/Aleutian_Islands) extending into the [Eastern Hemisphere](/Eastern_Hemisphere). &#91;41&#93; Alaska stands alone as the only U.S. state not part of the contiguous North American landmass; approximately 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory, comprising [British Columbia](/British_Columbia), separates it from [Washington](/Washington_(state)). While technically part of continental North America, it's rarely included in colloquial discussions of the term. Alaska is not part of the [contiguous U.S.](/Contiguous_United_States), often referred to as "[the Lower 48](/Outside_(Alaska))". Even its capital, [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska), though located on the mainland, lacks direct road access to the rest of the North American highway system. The largest lake in Alaska is [Lake Illiamna](/Iliamna_Lake).

Alaska shares borders with Canada's [Yukon](/Yukon) and [British Columbia](/British_Columbia) to the east (making it the sole state bordered exclusively by a [Canadian territory](/Provinces_and_territories_of_Canada)). The [Gulf of Alaska](/Gulf_of_Alaska) and the Pacific Ocean lie to the south and southwest. To the west, the [Bering Sea](/Bering_Sea), [Bering Strait](/Bering_Strait), and [Chukchi Sea](/Chukchi_Sea) form its boundary, while the Arctic Ocean stretches along its northern edge. Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's in the Bering Strait, with the Russian [Big Diomede Island](/Big_Diomede_Island) and Alaska's [Little Diomede Island](/Little_Diomede_Island) separated by a mere 3 miles (4.8 km). Alaska boasts a coastline longer than all other U.S. states combined. &#91;42&#93;

[Alaska's size compared with the contiguous states](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Alaska_size_comparison_Albers_equal-area_conic_projection.svg/640px-Alaska_size_comparison_Albers_equal-area_conic_projection.svg.png)
([Albers equal-area conic projection](/Albers_projection))

With a total area of 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km<sup>2</sup>), Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States. It is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state, Texas, and surpasses the combined area of Texas, California, and Montana. Alaska ranks as the seventh [largest subnational division in the world](/List_of_the_largest_country_subdivisions_by_area). If it were an independent nation, it would rank as the 18th largest country globally, comparable in size to [Iran](/Iran). &#91;43&#93;

Alaska's intricate coastline, including its numerous islands, stretches for nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km). The Aleutian Islands chain extends westward from the southern tip of the [Alaska Peninsula](/Alaska_Peninsula). Many active [volcanoes](/Volcano) dot the Aleutians and the coastal regions. For instance, [Mount Shishaldin](/Mount_Shishaldin) on [Unimak Island](/Unimak_Island) is a perpetually smoldering volcano rising to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific. This volcanic chain continues to [Mount Spurr](/Mount_Spurr), located west of Anchorage on the mainland. Geologists categorize Alaska as part of [Wrangellia](/Wrangellia), a vast geological region encompassing multiple states and Canadian provinces in the [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest), which is actively undergoing [continent building](/Plate_tectonics). &#91;44&#93;

One of the world's most extreme tidal ranges occurs in [Turnagain Arm](/Turnagain_Arm), just south of Anchorage, where tidal fluctuations can exceed 35 feet (10.7 m). &#91;45&#93;

Alaska is home to over 409,000 natural lakes, each at least one hectare in size. &#91;46&#93; Vast expanses of [marshlands](/Marshland) and wetland [permafrost](/Permafrost) cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km<sup>2</sup>), predominantly in the northern, western, and southwestern flatlands. Glacier ice blankets approximately 28,957 square miles (75,000 km<sup>2</sup>) of Alaska. &#91;47&#93; The [Bering Glacier](/Bering_Glacier), the largest glacier in North America, alone covers 2,008 square miles (5,200 km<sup>2</sup>). &#91;48&#93;

#### Regions

##### Southcentral

*   Main article: [Southcentral Alaska](/Southcentral_Alaska)

This is Alaska's most populous region, encompassing [Anchorage](/Anchorage), the [Matanuska-Susitna Valley](/Matanuska-Susitna_Valley), and the [Kenai Peninsula](/Kenai_Peninsula). It also includes the sparsely populated areas south of the [Alaska Range](/Alaska_Range) and west of the [Wrangell Mountains](/Wrangell_Mountains), as well as the [Prince William Sound](/Prince_William_Sound) area and the communities of [Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska) and [Valdez](/Valdez,_Alaska). &#91;49&#93;

##### Southeast

*   Main article: [Southeast Alaska](/Southeast_Alaska)

Also known as the Panhandle or the [Inside Passage](/Inside_Passage), this region is Alaska's closest point to the contiguous states. Consequently, it was the site of most initial non-indigenous settlement following the [Alaska Purchase](/Alaska_Purchase). The region is characterized by the [Alexander Archipelago](/Alexander_Archipelago) and the [Tongass National Forest](/Tongass_National_Forest), the largest national forest in the United States. It includes the state capital [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska), the former capital [Sitka](/Sitka,_Alaska), and [Ketchikan](/Ketchikan), which was once Alaska's largest city. &#91;50&#93; The [Alaska Marine Highway](/Alaska_Marine_Highway) serves as a critical transportation link throughout the area and to the wider country, as only three communities ([Haines](/Haines,_Alaska), [Hyder](/Hyder,_Alaska), and [Skagway](/Skagway,_Alaska)) have direct road access to the North American highway system. &#91;51&#93;

##### Interior

*   Main article: [Interior Alaska](/Interior_Alaska)

[Denali](/Denali), the highest peak in North America.

The Interior is Alaska's largest region, much of it remaining untouched wilderness. [Fairbanks](/Fairbanks,_Alaska) is the sole major city in this vast area. [Denali National Park and Preserve](/Denali_National_Park_and_Preserve) is located here, as is [Denali](/Denali), federally designated as Mount McKinley, the highest mountain on the North American continent.

##### North Slope

*   Main article: [Alaska North Slope](/Alaska_North_Slope)

The North Slope is primarily tundra, dotted with small villages. This region is renowned for its extensive crude oil reserves and encompasses both the [National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska](/National_Petroleum_Reserve%E2%80%93Alaska) and the [Prudhoe Bay Oil Field](/Prudhoe_Bay_Oil_Field). &#91;52&#93; The city of [Utqiaġvik](/Utqia%C4%A1vik,_Alaska), formerly known as Barrow, holds the distinction of being the northernmost city in the United States. The [Northwest Arctic area](/Northwest_Arctic_Borough,_Alaska), anchored by [Kotzebue](/Kotzebue,_Alaska) and including the [Kobuk River](/Kobuk_River) valley, is often considered part of this region, though the [Inupiat](/Inupiat_people) of the North Slope and the Northwest Arctic do not typically identify as a single people. &#91;53&#93;

##### Southwest

*   Main article: [Southwest Alaska](/Southwest_Alaska)

Southwest Alaska is a sparsely populated region extending roughly 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea coast. The majority of its population resides along the coastline. [Kodiak Island](/Kodiak_Island) is also situated within Southwest Alaska. This region is home to the expansive [Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta](/Yukon%E2%80%93Kuskokwim_Delta), one of the world's largest river deltas. Portions of the [Alaska Peninsula](/Alaska_Peninsula) are considered part of the Southwest, and the Aleutian Islands are often, though not always, grouped with this region. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

##### Aleutian Islands

*   Main article: [Aleutian Islands](/Aleutian_Islands)

Though entirely east of the [International Date Line](/International_Date_Line) (the peculiar bend in the line was established following the [U.S. acquisition of Alaska](/Alaska_Purchase)), the Aleutian Islands straddle the [180th meridian](/180th_meridian). This geographical anomaly means they contain both the westernmost ([Amatignak](/Amatignak_Island)) and the easternmost ([Semisopochnoi](/Semisopochnoi_Island).) points in the United States.

While typically classified as part of Southwest Alaska for economic purposes, the Aleutian Islands are sometimes considered a distinct geographical entity due to their separation from the mainland. This chain comprises over 300 small volcanic islands, stretching more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean. Some of these islands lie within the Eastern Hemisphere, but the [International Date Line](/International_Date_Line) was drawn to the west of [180°](/180th_meridian) to ensure the entire state, and by extension the North American continent, remained within the same legal day. Two of these islands, [Attu](/Attu_Island) and [Kiska](/Kiska), were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II. &#91;54&#93;

#### Land ownership

This section requires additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Alaska) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed. (January 2025) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

As of 2023, the [United States Bureau of Land Management](/United_States_Bureau_of_Land_Management) oversees 290 million surface and subsurface acres of public land, encompassing numerous [national forests](/United_States_National_Forest), national parks, [national wildlife refuges](/National_wildlife_refuge), &#91;55&#93; and federal mineral estate lands. &#91;56&#93; Of this total, the [Bureau of Land Management](/Bureau_of_Land_Management) directly manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), representing 23.8% of the state's area. The [Arctic National Wildlife Refuge](/Arctic_National_Wildlife_Refuge), managed by the [United States Fish and Wildlife Service](/United_States_Fish_and_Wildlife_Service), is the largest wildlife refuge in the world, spanning 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).

The state of Alaska itself owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), fulfilling its entitlement under the [Alaska Statehood Act](/Alaska_Statehood_Act). Portions of this acreage are periodically transferred to organized boroughs under statutory provisions for newly formed boroughs. Smaller tracts are designated for rural subdivisions and other homesteading opportunities, though these are seldom popular due to their often remote and roadless locations. The [University of Alaska](/University_of_Alaska), as a [land grant university](/Land_grant_university), also holds substantial acreage under its independent management.

An additional 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional and numerous local Native corporations, established under the [Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act](/Alaska_Native_Claims_Settlement_Act) (ANCSA) of 1971. [Regional Native corporation](/Alaska_Native_Regional_Corporation) [Doyon, Limited](/Doyon,_Limited) frequently advertises itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska. While ANCSA provisions initially allowed for the sale of these corporate landholdings on the open market starting in 1991, these provisions were repealed before they could be enacted. Consequently, the corporations retain title, often including subsurface rights—a privilege denied to individual Alaskans—but cannot sell the land. Individual Native allotments, however, are subject to open market sale.

Private interests hold the remaining land, constituting approximately one percent of the state. When Native corporation holdings are excluded, Alaska has by far the smallest percentage of privately owned land among all U.S. states.

##### Alaska Heritage Resources Survey

The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted [inventory](/Inventory) of all documented [historic](/Historic_site) and [prehistoric](/Prehistoric) sites within Alaska. Maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology, its inventory encompasses objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, generally those over fifty years old. As of January 31, 2012 &#91;update&#93;, over 35,000 sites had been reported. &#91;57&#93;

#### Cities, towns and boroughs

*   Further information: [List of cities in Alaska](/List_of_cities_in_Alaska) and [List of boroughs and census areas in Alaska](/List_of_boroughs_and_census_areas_in_Alaska)
*   See also: [List of Alaska locations by per capita income](/List_of_Alaska_locations_by_per_capita_income)

[Anchorage](/Anchorage) is Alaska's largest city.
[Fairbanks](/Fairbanks,_Alaska), Alaska's second-largest city and by a significant margin the largest city in [Alaska's interior](/Alaska_Interior).
[Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska), Alaska's third-largest city and [its capital](/List_of_capitals_in_the_United_States).
[Bethel](/Bethel,_Alaska), the largest city in the [Unorganized Borough](/Unorganized_Borough) and in [rural Alaska](/The_Bush_(Alaska)).
[Homer](/Homer,_Alaska), showing (from bottom to top) the edge of downtown, [its airport](/Homer_Airport), and [the Spit](/Homer_Spit).
[Utqiaġvik](/Utqia%C4%A1vik,_Alaska) (Eben Hopson Middle School in Browerville neighborhood shown), colloquially known for many years as "Top of the World," is the northernmost city in the United States.
[Cordova](/Cordova,_Alaska), established in the early 20th century to support the [Kennecott Mines](/Kennecott_Mines) and the [Copper River and Northwestern Railway](/Copper_River_and_Northwestern_Railway), has persisted as a fishing community since their closure.
Main Street in [Talkeetna](/Talkeetna).

Unlike most U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into [counties](/County_(United_States)), similar to Louisiana's [parishes](/List_of_parishes_in_ Louisiana). Instead, it is divided into [boroughs](/List_of_boroughs_and_census_areas_in_Alaska). &#91;58&#93; Delegates to the [Alaska Constitutional Convention](/Alaska_Constitutional_Convention) sought to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system, opting for a unique model. &#91;59&#93; Sixteen boroughs, functioning similarly to counties in other states, encompass the more densely populated areas of the state. However, unlike county-equivalents elsewhere, these boroughs do not cover the entire state. The unincorporated territory is known as the [Unorganized Borough](/Unorganized_Borough,_Alaska).

The Unorganized Borough lacks its own government. For statistical and reporting purposes, the [U.S. Census Bureau](/U.S._Census_Bureau), in collaboration with the state, has divided it into 11 [census areas](/Census_area). Alaska is further divided into 34 recording districts, each managed centrally by a state [recorder](/Recorder_of_deeds). All districts adhere to uniform acceptance criteria and fee schedules for document recording.

While most U.S. states employ a three-tiered governmental structure (state/county/township), Alaska primarily uses a two-tiered system (state/borough). Due to its low population density, most of the land falls within the [Unorganized Borough](/Unorganized_Borough). As its name suggests, this area is administered directly by the state government, without an intermediate borough authority. In 2000, this status applied to 57.71% of Alaska's land area, encompassing 13.05% of its population. &#91;60&#93;

In 1975, the city of Anchorage merged with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough, forming the Municipality of Anchorage, which includes the city proper and surrounding communities like Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian. Fairbanks operates with a distinct borough, the [Fairbanks North Star Borough](/Fairbanks_North_Star_Borough), and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).

[Anchorage](/Anchorage,_Alaska) remains Alaska's most populous city, with 291,247 residents as of 2020. &#91;61&#93; The highest [per capita income](/Alaska_locations_by_per_capita_income) in Alaska is found in [Denali](/Denali_Borough,_Alaska), with $42,245. [Yakutat](/Yakutat,_Alaska), Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are recognized as the four [largest cities in the U.S. by area](/List_of_U.S._cities_by_area).

**Cities and census-designated places (by population)**

The [2020 United States Census](/2020_United_States_census) identified 355 incorporated cities and [census-designated places](/Census-designated_place) (CDPs) within Alaska. &#91;62&#93; This count includes four unified municipalities, essentially functioning as [consolidated city–counties](/Consolidated_city%E2%80%93county). A significant number of these communities are situated in the remote expanse of Alaska known as "[The Bush](/The_Bush_(Alaska))" and are disconnected from the contiguous North American road network. The table below lists the 100 most populous cities and CDPs in Alaska, ordered by population.

As of the 2020 U.S. Census, 733,391 individuals resided in Alaska, with 16,655 (2.27%) not living within an incorporated city or CDP. &#91;61&#93; Approximately three-quarters of this group resided in urban and suburban areas adjacent to city limits in Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer, and Wasilla. CDPs for these specific neighborhoods have not been established by the U.S. Census Bureau since the [1980 United States Census](/1980_United_States_census), which designated seven CDPs in the Ketchikan area. The remaining population was dispersed across Alaska, both within organized boroughs and the Unorganized Borough, in largely isolated locales. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

