The [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau) reported Alaska's population at 733,391 as of April 1, 2020, marking a 3.3% increase since the [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census). &#91;6&#93; In the 2010 census, Alaska's population stood at 710,231, a 13.3% rise from 626,932 in 2000.

In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th most populous state, ahead of only [Vermont](/Vermont) and [Wyoming](/Wyoming). &#91;76&#93; It remains the least densely populated state and one of the most sparsely populated regions globally, with a density of 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km<sup>2</sup>). Wyoming, by comparison, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km<sup>2</sup>). &#91;77&#93; Despite its vast size, Alaska ranks as the tenth wealthiest state in terms of per capita income. &#91;78&#93; As of 2018 &#91;update&#93;, due to its population size, it was one of 14 U.S. states still utilizing a single telephone [area code](/Telephone_numbering_plan). &#91;79&#93;

According to HUD's 2022 [Annual Homeless Assessment Report](/Annual_Homeless_Assessment_Report_to_Congress), an estimated 2,320 individuals were experiencing homelessness in Alaska. &#91;80&#93; &#91;81&#93;

